Uses Standard Deck of 4 suits. Deal ten
cards each and one to a discard pile. Any
held card not in a set (3+ of same rank)
or a run (3+ sequence of same suit) is
"deadwood", scoring its rank (10 for face
cards). On your turn: draw from the deck
or the discard pile, then discard a card.
With less than 10 deadwood, you may
then knock, revealing your sets and runs.
After, your opponent adds cards to your
sets and runs. The player with the lowest
deadwood total (opponent winning ties)
scores the difference between totals,
+10 if they didn't knock, +20 for knocking
with zero deadwood. Play to 100.
Uses Standard Deck of 4 suits. Deal 13
cards each and flip the top card of the
deck face up to determine trump suit.
Dealer plays a card, opponent plays one
following suit if possible. Highest trump
wins the trick, otherwise the highest card
of the starting suit wins. Winner draws
the face-up deck card into their hand
and leads the next trick, loser draws the
next deck card into their hand, and the
top card of the deck is turned face-up
(this does not change the trump suit).
When the deck runs out, continue but
scoring won tricks instead of drawing
cards. Most scored tricks wins.
Uses Standard Deck of 4 suits with two-
person teams. Each player is dealt a
hand of four cards and four cards are
dealt face-up to the table. Play is
simultaneous, with no turns. Your goal is
to have all four cards in your hand of the
same value. If a card you want is on the
table, pick it up, put it in your hand, and
then discard a card to replace it. If the
action comes to a standstill another four
cards are dealt. When you have acquired
a complete set you cannot declare this
yourself. Instead, you must use a pre-
arranged signal to inform your partner,
who then announces "Kemps" for a point.
If you call Kemps erroneously, the other
team gets a point. If you think you have
spotted the other team's signal, you can
call "Kemps against" to receive a point,
otherwise the other team does.

Cards 2-K in 5 color suits. Place aces
between players as sites. Deal eight cards
to each player. On a players turn 1)
Discard a card face up on a site of the
same suit OR 2) Place a card on an
expedition. Expedition cards are placed in
ascending order, though not necessarily
consecutively. The handshake cards (JQK)
may only start an expedition. Afterwards,
draw a card from the stock or from a
site. You can't draw a card you discarded
this turn. The game ends AS SOON as the
last card is drawn from the stock.
Scoring: For each expedition: Add the
numbers on the cards and subtract 20.
Multiply the result by (1 + number of
handshake cards). If there are eight or
more cards in an expedition, add 20
bonus points. If no cards are placed on
an expedition, then it scores 0.
Cards numbered 3-35 (with a dot). Count
out 9 cards and set them aside. The
remaining 24 cards form a face-down
draw deck. Flip over the top card, this is
the active card. Deal out the other cards
(facedown) to use as chips:
3-4p: 11 chips, 5p: 9 chips, 6p: 7 chips.
On your turn: 1) Place a chip on the
active card, and play passes to your left.
You may not pass if you have no chips.
2) Take the active card and add it to your
play area. Also, take the chips on it and
add them to your hidden supply. Then
turn over a new active card. The game
ends when you take the last active card
and there are no cards left in the draw
deck. Scoring: Each card in your play
area is worth its face value in points. If a
card is part of a sequential run, then only
count the lowest card in that sequence.
Cards 2-10 in 6 color suits. Layout nine
Flags (unused cards) in a line between
both players. Shuffle and deal out seven
cards to each player. On a players turn,
select one card and place it face up on
your side, then draw one card. After
three cards are placed on either side of
each flag, then the flag is claimed with
the best rank.
Rank Order (3 Cards): Straight Flush,
Three of a Kind, Flush, Straight, Sum of
Cards.
Game End: When someone successfully
claims three adjacent Flags or any five
Flags with better formations, the game
immediately ends.
Standard deck of 4 suits with Mah Jong,
Dog, Phoenix, and Dragon. Each player is
dealt 8 cards (option for Grand Tichu),
followed by 6 more cards (option for
Tichu). Each player then passes a card
face down to every player.
Declaring Tichu: Before a player plays
their first card, they may declare Tichu. If
they do and they get rid of all their cards
first, their team gets 100 points. If they
fail, their team loses 100 points. Grand
Tichu can only be declared before viewing
your ninth card for 200/-200 points.
Gameplay: The active player plays a card
combination. The next player plays a
higher combination or passes. After three
consecutive passes, the player who played
the last combination wins the trick. (And
leads the next trick)
Mah Jong: Leads the opening trick, but
isn't required to play. When played (has a
value of 1), the player makes a wish for a
card (2-A) and the next player who can
legally fufill the wish must play it.
Dog: Pass the lead to your partner. Can
only be played as the lead card.
Phoenix: 1) Joker (Value 2-A) in every
card combination except bombs. 2)
Single card. Worth half point higher than
the last played card with the exception of
the dragon.
Dragon: Highest single card and unable
to be a part of a sequence. If the trick is
won with the dragon, the trick is given
away to an opponent of your choice. If
the trick with the dragon is won with a
bomb, that player can take the trick,
including the dragon, for himself.
Positive Status: 1-10 star suit, three 2x
Negative Status: -5, 1/2, T (Thief)
Deal out money cards (heart, club, spade,
diamond) and place status cards
facedown. Flip status card & start bidding.
Positive cards: If you pass, take your
money back. When everyone passes, the
winner keeps the status card face up and
money is permanently removed. Negative
cards: First player to pass, takes the
status card and keeps his bid. Other
players bids are lost. The Thief forces a
player to discard a positive status card of
their choice (or next one acquired). Player
who takes possession starts the next bid.
When the fourth multipler (2x or 0.5x)
card is flipped, Game Ends immediately.
Player(s) with the least money loses.
Player with most status points wins.
5 suits. 3p: 1 9 4p: 1 Q
In clockwise order, each player plays a
single card that must be the same color
as the first card if possible. Otherwise, he
can play any other color.
1. Lowest player gets highest card.
2. Highest player gets remaining cards.
3. Highest player leads next trick.
If several highest cards are played, last
one played is highest. If several lowest
cards are played, last one played is
lowest. If all cards are equal, last card is
highest, second last card is lowest.
Scoring: If a player has only one or two
cards in a certain color, he receives the
face value of each card. If a player has
more than two cards in a certain color,
he only receives 1 point for each of those
cards.
Card Combinations: 5 card straight, full
house (value of the trio gives the higher
combination), three of a kind, consecutive
pairs, pair, single card. Aces are high.
Bombs (Four of a kind or a straight in
the same suit) may be played at any time
during a round and beats all other card
combinations. Bombs can be beaten by
stronger bombs. Five+ card straight is a
higher combination than four card bombs.
Points: The tricks won by the player out
last are given to the player out first and
their hand cards go to the opposing team.
Then the round is scored: 5s are 5 points,
10s and Kings are 10 points, Dragon is 25
points, Phoenix is -25 points. If two
teammates finish first and second they
get 200 points and the round ends. The
first team to get 1000 points wins.
1-8 in 6 suits, 8 face cards as another
"suit". Deal out every card. On a turn, a
player takes one card from his hand, lays
it face down, slides it to a player of his
choice and declares the suit. The player
receiving the card can either:
Accept the card, says either "true"
or "false", then reveals the card. If wrong,
she keeps the card on the table in front
of her face up. If right, the player who
gave her the card takes it.
Peeks at the card, then Passes it to
another player, either saying the original
or new suit. This new player can accept
or pass. If everyone has seen the card,
the last player must accept it. Whoever
lost a challenge, begins the next round.
Game End: If a player runs out of cards
or has four cards of the same suit, this
player loses and everyone else wins.
Uses Standard Deck of 4 suits. Cards are
dealt into eight cascades, where every
card is visible. There are four foundations
and four free cells. The free cells can
contain only one card at a time. The top
cards of the cascades and the cards in
the free cells can be moved. In the
cascades, you can build down in
alternating colors. For example, you can
put a card on another one if its rank is
smaller by one and their color is
different. In the foundations you can
build up in suit, starting from the ace.
The goal is to move every card to the
foundations.
